'''Consumer culture theory''' is the study of [[consumption choice]]s and behaviors from a social and cultural point of view, as opposed to an [[Economics|economic]] or [[psychological]] one. It does not offer a grand unifying theory but "refers to a family of theoretical perspectives that address the dynamic relationships between consumer actions, the marketplace, and cultural meanings".<ref name="CCT1">{{cite journal|last1=Arnould|first1=E. J.|last2=Thompson|first2=C. J.|year=2005|title=Consumer culture theory (CCT): Twenty Years of Research|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=31|issue=4|pages=868–882|url=http://econpapers.repec.org/article/ucpjconrs/v_3a31_3ay_3a2005_3ai_3a4_3ap_3a868-882.htm|doi=10.1086/426626}}</ref> Reflective of a [[Postmodernism|post-modernist]] society, it views cultural meanings as being numerous and fragmented<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Firat|first1=A. F.|last2=Venkatesh|first2=A.|year=1995|title=Liberatory Postmodernism and the Reenchantment of Consumption|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=22|issue=3|pages=239–267|jstor=2489612|doi=10.1086/209448}}</ref> and hence views culture as an amalgamation of different groups and shared meanings, rather than a homogeneous construct (such as the American culture). Consumer culture is viewed as "social arrangement in which the relations between lived culture and social resources, between meaningful ways of life and the symbolic and material resources on which they depend, are mediated through markets"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Arnould|first=E. J.|year=2006|title=Consumer culture theory: retrospect and prospect|journal=European Advances in Consumer Research|volume=7|issue=1|pages=605–607|url=http://www.acrwebsite.org/volumes/eacr/vol7/EuropeanVolume7_105.pdf|accessdate=14 August 2010}}</ref> and consumers as part of an interconnected system of commercially produced products and images which they use to construct their identity and orient their relationships with others.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kozinets|first1=R. V.|year=2001|title=Utopian Enterprise: Articulating the Meanings of Star Trek’s Culture of Consumption|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=28|issue=3|pages=67–88|jstor=254324|doi=10.1086/321948}}</ref>
== Methodology == There is a widely held misperception by people outside CCT researchers that this field is oriented toward the study of [[Consumption (economics)|consumption]] contexts.<ref name="CCT1" /> Memorable study contexts, such as the [[Harley-Davidson]] subculture<ref name="bikes">{{cite journal|last1=Schouten|first1=J.|last2=McAlexander|first2=J. H.|year=1995|title=Subcultures of Consumption: An Ethnography of the New Bikers|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=22|issue=3|pages=43–.,./61|url=http://classes.bus.oregonstate.edu/winter-07/ba492/Subcultures%20of%20Consumption.pdf|doi=10.1086/209434}}</ref> or the [[Burning Man]] festival<ref name="burning">{{cite journal|last=Kozinets|first=Robert V|year=2002|title=Can Consumers Escape the Market? Emancipatory Illuminations from Burning Man|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|publisher=University of Chicago Press|volume=29|issue=1|pages=20–38|url=http://econpapers.repec.org/article/ucpjconrs/v_3a29_3ay_3a2002_3ai_3a1_3ap_3a20-38.htm|accessdate=7 August 2010|doi=10.1086/339919}}</ref> probably fueled this perspective, which is far from the theory development aim of this school of thought.
While CCT is often associated with [[qualitative methodology|qualitative methodologies]], such as interviews, case studies, [[Ethnography|ethnographic]], as well as 'netnographic' methods<ref>{{Cite journal|title = The Field Behind the Screen: Using Netnography for Marketing Research in Online Communities|url = http://journals.ama.org/doi/abs/10.1509/jmkr.39.1.61.18935|journal = Journal of Marketing Research|date = February 1, 2002|issn = 0022-2437|pages = 61–72|volume = 39|issue = 1|doi = 10.1509/jmkr.39.1.61.18935|first = Robert V.|last = Kozinets}}</ref> which are well adapted to study the experiential, sociological and cultural aspects of consumption, these are not a prerequisite to CCT contribution (Arnould & Thompson 2005).
== Fields of study == Arnould & Thompson<ref name="CCT1" /> identifies four research programs in CCT: *Consumer identity projects, such as Schau & Gilly<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schau|first1=H. J.|last2=Gilly|first2=M. C.|year=2003|title=We Are What We Post? Self-Presentation in Personal Web Space|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=30|issue=4|pages=384–404|jstor=3132017|doi=10.1086/378616}}</ref> study on personal web space, which studied how consumers create a coherent self through marketer-produced materials *Marketplace culture, such as Schouten & McAlexander<ref name="bikes" /> study on the Harley-Davidson subculture, which looked at consumers as culture producers. This research program builds particularly on Maffesoli's concept of neo-tribes<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Time of the Tribes: The Decline of Individualism in Mass Society|url = https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=36elPGofHRUC&oi=fnd&pg=PP1&dq=maffesoli+tribes&ots=hV24JGRbE9&sig=oBtoxgJANeqzP2WzuijhDr6y-zY|publisher = SAGE|date = 1995-12-05|isbn = 9781848609532|first = Michel|last = Maffesoli}}</ref> Studies of consumer tribes have focused, for example, on clubbing culture and surf culture.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Learning to be tribal: facilitating the formation of consumer tribes|url = http://www.emeraldinsight.com/doi/abs/10.1108/03090561311306886|journal = European Journal of Marketing|date = May 24, 2013|issn = 0309-0566|pages = 813–832|volume = 47|issue = 5/6|doi = 10.1108/03090561311306886}}</ref> *Mass-mediated marketplace ideologies and consumers' interpretive strategies, such as Kozinets<ref name="burning" /> study of the Burning Man Festival, which looked at consumer ideologies and identities are influenced by economic and cultural globalisation and how cultural product systems orient consumers toward certain ideologies or identity projects. *Sociohistoric patterning of consumption, such as Holt<ref>{{cite journal|last=Holt|first=D. B.|year=1998|title=Does Cultural Capital Structure American Consumption|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=25|issue=1|pages=1–25|doi=10.1086/209523}}</ref> study which looked at the influence of social capital on consumption choices.
