{{nihongo|'''Kōdai-ji'''|高台寺|''Kōdai-ji''}}, formally identified as {{nihongo|Jubuzan Kōdai-ji|鷲峰山高台寺|''Jubuzan Kōdai-ji''}}, is a temple of the [[Rinzai school]] of [[Zen]] [[Buddhism]] in [[Higashiyama-ku, Kyoto|Higashiyama-ku]], [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]]—the largest subtemple of the [[Kennin-ji]] branch.

==History==
[[File:Toyotomi Hideyoshi 1601.jpg|thumb|upright|This portrait of Toyotomi Hideyoshi is an Important Cultural Asset of Japan.]]
It was established in 1606 by the nun [[Kōdai-in]] (often known by the title Kita no [[Mandokoro]]), who was the widow of [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]], to pray for her late husband. The principal image is a statue of [[Gautama Buddha|Shaka]].

The gardens of Kōdai-ji are a [[Cultural Properties of Japan|nationally designated]] [[Monuments of Japan|Historic Site]] and [[Monuments of Japan|Place of Scenic Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=401&item_id=1661 |title=高台寺庭園 |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>

The temple possesses a number of objects designated as Important Cultural Assets. Among these are the Main Gate and the Spirit Hall, noted for its use of ''[[maki-e]].'' The temple is nicknamed the ''maki-e'' temple." It also holds paintings, including one of Hideyoshi, as well as textiles, and a bronze [[Bell (instrument)|bell]] with an inscription dating it to 1606.

{{wide image|Japan - Flickr - GregTheBusker (17).jpg|600px|[[Japanese rock garden|Japanese gravel garden]] at Kōdai-ji}}

